One session. This was a lot of fun, and I have no idea if it was hard. At any rate, I love this beach, I luv climbin'. Thanks for the spot, Daniella.
Another one-mover! This time to my favorite kind of hold! The sit feels like it'll be quite a bit harder.
This might be my favorite line at Mickey's. Really had to work for this one. From sopping wet to dry enough. Thanks Damien.

Alone at the boulders with a washed-up, dying crab. Tried to get him back near the water, but he kept crawling up to the boulder. He looked really sick and resigned in a dying crustacean kind of way. Then I got kinda sad in a not-dying, but contemplating-my-lot-on-this-planet kind of way. Anyways, I sure am glad I'm alive and I'm able to go climbing.
A few years ago I looked at this and thought I'd never do it. Rose move!
I'm 98% sure I did this. Eliminated the blocky foothold out to the left and everything right of the smile crimp.  Really liked the pinch move! Thanks for saving me from the tree Damien.
Great start to the Hoedown. Gettin' the jitters out.
Highball Hoedown! I'm pretty sure this is the first 6 I've flashed. So good, so spooky. Thanks to all the Hoedowners. I'll probably remember this forever.
Never wanted to try this until the sand got really high and the holds really dry. Fun!
Sometimes it's hard to try hard. Especially when you're alone and pumped.
Cold granite hurts! Yosemite feet are are like no other feet.
Really cold, creaky start to the day. I completely understand this climb's reputation now. Very cool.
Went into the blinding sun for a while. Glad I waited it out. Resting means everything.  Great climb.
This is pretty much just as good as the full diamond. Less stress. Very fun. Is there a Diamond Right? Felt way hard.
The unexpected result of having a good crew. Send train with Shannon et al. Thanks for the spray-down Mark!
Great end to a weirdly productive bouldering day. Best crew, hard to beat a day like this. Thanks Damien, Shannon, Laura for shouting me up this. Thanx Cole for being a betababe.
Don't care what anybody says... party-trick boulders are the tightest ever. Double 'copter nemesis. Props to Damey!
Proud to say I can now climb v4.
Reach 'n' latch.
Classic. Topping out is no guarantee.
I'm pretty sure this was hard. Shade's the best.
Barely. Just barely held it together. Took it to the top as soon as I stuck the first move. Thank god.

That view tho.
Thank you JT for being a human step-ladder. Couldn't have cracked this one without you.

This was fantastic and emotionally draining. Waited for a break in the rain, chalked wet holds, stuffed a towel in the crack... Still underestimated the wet top-out. Scary without spotters, thank god for fist jams. Taking full points.
Suddenly standing up was possible!
A few tries. All this friction lets me pretend to be a strong guy. Thnx for catching me Cole.
This problem is sort of a turd... but I love smearing my knees and squeezing. I hate that I'm going to do the sit someday. Probably soon?

Fun! Worked during sunset after a long session in the cave. Sent second go the next morning. Maybe hard?

Part two of the shoulder test day. Seems like everything is holding together! Press!

Wow! This is real life? Not to get greedy, but wish this boulder had even more...
Felt so much easier today. Bungled my beta and still got it. Really great moves. Perfect day trip with Stacey.
I really don't know. The moves are subtle and pretty powerful. I tried hard with good conditions until I did it. I'll probably end up downgrading once I actually climb this grade.
Worth the skin... probably.

Fun! Sit felt not as fun. Will I return?
Sometimes I'll look at an old-school problem and think "that looks pretty easy." Then I'll realize Bachar did it and I'll end up flashing on my twentieth attempt.

Okay here's a theory: by the time you're actually able to climb v10 this feels soft because it's short and pretty clear what you have to do. Also gym climbing or something. But if you're not able to climb v10 it feels like it could be v10 because who knows? Or if it was on a route you'd be like "That's a v10 crux! I'm a 5.14 climber!" Or it's just not v10. Part one of the soft-serve dub-dub. Proud.
Not as tough in the cold, but  decidedly not soft. Giving Tree on the other hand, is Firm. Hard even.
Part two of the soft-serve dub-dub. Stacey gets extra credit for braving the altitude and frozen river maze. Also this climb was fun and I would have given it stars, but why start now?
Spreading my wings with lil bro and Stace after the turkey feast. I'm feeling Conor's reasoning on this one...feels just barely a cut above the 9s this season. Two sessions.
Fun with the Fresno crew! Either this needs a downgrade or Ataturk deserves an upgrade...
Cool! Took a few tries to believe in the lock-off.
If not for the sharp hole, this would probably get climbed a lot. I love grainy rock.
The first move was hard. My arms are short. The bump was hard. First climb in Bishop. Must be soft.
I was surprised to find myself at each move. Must fit me really well. Four tries?
At first I thought I might destroy my shoulder. Actual fear. Warmed up more, kept that thing flexed. Thanks Cole, for beta and belief, as always.
Looked like I would fit in there.
I love this kind of thing. Kept the heels forever.
Are there more Avenger climbs?
Really wouldn't have ever thought I could do something hard based around crimps and pockets. I love my friends.
Left my arm in that hole. Gotta pick up a new sport.
Sometimes I dread seeing crowds at a crag. I really want to be alone, but then this happens, and you're like... oh tight.
I guess you have to pull harder sometimes.

I've gotten so inconsistent about logging easy/ moderate boulders, but I'll log this one because I've heard it mentioned four-thousand times since starting climbing a decade ago. I finally made it to Bishop. It was good.
What a relief. Very odd that this doesn't get climbed more often. Maybe Across the Trax can happen for me now.
This felt so hard before. That left hand especially... Today it just all made sense. Guess everyone thinks it's easy. Yeah me too guys.
Thank you Stace for slogging out the hike. And thanks to the wind for blowing my pads away. No thanks to the fire or the snowstorm.
I fell onto the tree! Sent next go. Power shuffling.
Didn't feel easy.
Great movement. The hike was a rude reminder about elevation.

That's right. Calling this an onsight. Braved the mosquito field, onsighted the approach. Made some jangus tape gloves, sat down, and got totally snaked. Really psyched on this one. I miss crack climbing.
Hot up here! Seeking shade with Stace.
I think I climbed this weird. Mantled to the right, toehooked. Back in Squamish!
While rehabbing my blown-out right knee. This thing finally made sense!
Challenger dessert. Toughie.

Power! Funny how I thought I could flash but instead I didn't and then I sprained my ankle on PBR prow instead. ha.

It's all about jumping from the right angle. Also helps if rockstars are standing right next to you. So close on Pride!

ascents.comment: Weird November conditions. Air was wet, rock was... something like wet. Somehow I stuck. Turkey power.
Dangling like a fool. Had a great time.
With Kirk.
When are fingers really, truly warmed up?
I guess so? Thought it might just be v5, but then I tried to repeat it and couldn't.
Soft if you do it, impossible otherwise.  I'm happy.
Not my favorite size of grips. Had to do it for the dub-dub and juggalo victory swing. Woot-woot!
Biceps 'n' elbows
Stace did the emotional labor. I did the chuffing. Nilo brought the psych for round 2. That guy is really good at climbing.
Kept switching methods until Nilo did it the first way we tried. Had to bark like a dog to keep up. First proud dub-dub, best group of friends. Yes.
Nilo!
Night climbing is tight. Questing with Wray and Nilo. Pulled on to test some moves... should have tried to flash! Drop-offs are safe and The Seam is still very hard for me.
Body Flinglish! Last move is harder than it looks from the ground. Far better climbers than I have taken 10, so I'll do the same. Wray 'n' Joe closing in on the Nazi arete!
Crazy that this went unnoticed. Didn't climb the way I thought it would. V10 seems about right. Keenan!
Really easy to not do the last move.
Great day w/ Ian.
Only took a decade or so. Accept pain.
What? Did I just have fun at Mortar?!?
It's Friday the 13th; the apocalypse draws near. I'm a man desperate to squirm my way up a pile of choss before the rain falls. Strange times indeed.
First post-apocalyptic points on the board. I remember this feeling really tweaky in the past... I must've gotten better at heel-hooking and MCL-mindfulness since then. It is nice to be back. Yes.
Logging this almost a year after. This was really hard for a long time... had to get better at punchy, hateful crimping.
Another late-log. Kinda almost sorta flashed... but of course didn't. Instead I regressed massively for hours then somehow put it together in the hot, hot sun. About a week later my finger exploded.
Rad! Many methods seemed viable, but I ended up using a drop-knee. Glad I sent before the thundersoak stormed up. Guidebook says 10... sure, yes, why not?

Really felt like this was gonna happen quickly. Suited me well. But... it took three visits. I'd blame the heat, but like... I know. Met my first Squamish bear! The start of a long, weird "last" night.

The witching hour drew nigh. I had become more tape than man, and the Weirdness was within and about me. There, in a hole in the northern wild, I found myself utterly soaked in blood, thirsty, and pulling my ass off the ground of my pit-prison for perhaps a final round of self-flagellation. Ass lifted, I extended a bloodied limb skyward and committed once more to the no-fall zone. Staring down the second move, I sensed that my body had not yet paid sufficient penance for its dab. Like Wayne before me, I arose from the darkness compromised further, bloodier still, my sins ever-compounding.
So here's me, rounding up and logging dab laps on the far side of midnight so that I can tell myself I'm still a man of double-double caliber. Darkness is my ally.

Good day groupthinking with Sacramento crew.
Winter never ends.
Warm-ups for dummy: make sure not to flash so you can take all your skin off running idiot laps in the sun. :)
THIS is climbing.

Underclung the begunning 4 bicepian wunda gunnin'
w/ Nilo & Maggie

I finally had the heart to return to the ~~path not taken~~
10 years of practice was all it took to make this feel v10.
I still struggle with the notion of style. "My style," my "anti-style," & c... For me, I can just say that I like when hard feels easy. Shouts out to Bernat, Miguel, and kneepads.
Really liked the movement. If not for the bully block lurking by your left shoulder on Dr. Evil... this would be an excellent boulder.
The day I met Alan, Kim & Billy. This was a phenomenal summer. Also Gibb's Cave finally doesn't feel insanely difficult, so I must be getting better at something. Tite.
"What the fuck. WHAT the Fuck!? What. The. Fuccck!!"
LAYLA! <3
Always thought this seemed like a bad skin investment in the summer. Glad I FA+FO.

Wray fucking sent Sloppy Poppy!

w/ Nat and co.
Martin is a Machine.
So many new friends this summer. My heart is full.

One of the best boulders I've climbed.
Leona, Zach, Nat, Freya, Jonah, Super. Saiyan.
Date? Very nearly flattened by Paddle-Dyno Zach.
Finally picked this lil fucker up. Without a doubt the most attempts I've ever given to a single move. Also mantled it upside-down. PROUD.

Finally! w/ Leona + Zach + Camil, who sent shortly after I did, and in far smoother style. Still can't believe this was his first 7... and he's never climbed v6. An absolute graceful maniac, that guy.
Not sure why it's spelt' this way. Such a great climb, though. Def the hardest offwidth I've done.
Holy moly, Nat! You flashed? Hero shit.
Triple toe! Punted and then didn't. There were 28 people at this boulder.
Lead with the knees, shoot from the hip. I'll take my points where I can get 'em.
Low
More time and skin spent here than on any other 'V10.' *shrug emoji*
Managed to span to the better hold zone from the most twisted kneebar. Sun's out.
Years. And the better part of one lost to ligamentous violence to the left hand. So much of life is return and renewal.
After dropping the end years and years ago, I've finally regained whatever I had then... but like... better.

Of two minds and two bodies. Ballet below the waist, trash compactor above.
Heartbreak hurts so so much.
A punchy diversion from running laps on mystery pocket, ever discovering ways to drop the top from the bottom. Tempted to take the guidebook 11, because ego... buuuuut...

Rewards positioning more than effort and perhaps even more than skin condition. A double-double—soft or not— is a treat. Couldn't have really gotten any closer to success on the low without succeeding. Will I return? Someday, probably. Heartbreak persists; grief is nonlinear.

Did it from one move in while tuning beta…felt strategically silly. Fortunately sent next go, despite bungling the middle. Good crew out! Nilo, Maggie, Addie, Gunn, Mike &c. Kitten’s (Toast?) first day out climbing!
Sussed kneebar wearing sneakers and no pad… and with my cat in my puffy hood, so technically I didn’t flash.  Except… I did.
Literally hard for v10. I can't overstate how terrible this climb is. There's no other boulder I've tried even remotely as many times as this absolute pile. Looking forward to doing the sit fml.

Precisely the same grade as the stand.

Chinese Connection opening linked! Overlapping halves! Technically.
Then degloved my hand on the uber-classic “Da Funk.”
Really confirming that Mortar works better when you don’t need it to.
Almost not worth it… but actually totally worth it because everything is worth exactly what it’s worth.

The thought of doing this into Go-go Gadget seems an insult not only to the Kraken but to the sport of climbing and the broader concepts of coherence and beauty. And yet, if it turns out that I never end up doing that, it won't be for any reason other than it's too damn hard.
Sharp. Barely shindexable for me.
In the end, I think the toehook simply stays when we’re fresh and willing to pull hard.
Toaster paced the day. Made the attempt count. Thanks, kitten.
I guess maybe this is easier than the gecko after all. Houdini shoulder dab-evasion rose move.
I dabbed and I’m proud of myself.
Snow flurries coming in. Kept the Toast toasty. First (completed) climb out here.
ascents.sectorName: Cabin Fever / The Perimeter / The Death Scream Area

ascents.comment: Did as much as I could with what remains.
There are good reasons it’s known to be good.
I love kneeing choss. This thing is actually loads of fun.

First boulder I touched in Utah. Session one yielded big punt energy and egregious heel delamination. Session two provided; I just needed to find myself where I belong: in a queue of 49 frothing dudes, each giving his pound of flesh, collectively doing our part to love this rock to death.

Keys to success, in order: 
1. Whatever the opposite of loneliness is~
2. A plan— your own or someone else’s~
3. Fresh tape~

Bouldering is a team sport; shouts out Chaarmander for work done and demonstrated.
Absolute skin destroyer. Proud of myself for climbing something this horrendously un-comfy and "anti-style."
Immediately re-split another finger as I pulled my ass off the ground. Toaster topped the boulder via the Mountaineer's Tree Route. Proud.
Zero-percent chance that I'd have done this without the right squad. And it's a good thing, too... seeing as I essentially climbed this four times. True rock climbing. Dub-dub & 50th v10 :P

Last boulder of the trip. Running on fumes, a Pop Tart, trash skin, borrowed psych, heavy feelings lurking, Sour Patches, bitter sweets, imminent goodbyes. Broken wholes don't seem to mend; might just be we build anew, bit by borrowed bit.
More Blood. More white leather slip-on. I am the One-shoed kook. The boulder is the bell. I am the clapper.
Peak experience. Yes: David, David, Riley, Scott, Carina, The Toast. Yes. <3

A boulder with classic three-act structure: first you climb a boulder to get in position to climb a boulder, then you climb the boulder, and then after you've climbed the boulder, you just have to climb a tall boulder. 
W/ Jacques ++. Took a salty dip. Toast was ambivalent about the ocean.

Babyfan ftw. Canadian Tyre + AA Batteries + Natural Nat's Calm Cruising Clinic = dry enough. The Portal is becoming a personal stash of heartbreakers... maybe my shadow self is masterminding a masterplan; letdowns might actually be rehearsals. Repetition compulsions beget eventual redemption, integration, and self-actualization. To wit, let us continue investing in pelvic awareness, LCL mindfulness, flexor tendons, antihydral, and battery-powered fans for an insane triple-double cleanup in the not-too-distant future.

One bear shut down 1,000 boulders. A rare post-resignation send made rarer still as a last-minute pre-golf warmup. w/ my dear boy Nat. Very few comfortable positions, and yet somehow the moves feel cool. Squamish remains the best.
Knee-searching is the new soul-searching. Note to future self: You're more than you think; it always takes about a week of Squamish to get your skin right.

Some hot takes: 1. Temps don't matter. 2. Climbing without your knees is bad technique. 3. The Solution Comp is terrible for toehooking.

Thanks, Ondra, for making your comp slipper available to the masses. It’d be amazing if LaSpo could engineer a version that isn’t single-use, but alas… I suppose this is simply the $2500 CAD price we pay for secure toe-hooks.

What I thought I could wrangle as a consolation after an Egg-scrambled knee, motor-mangled van, and trauma-primed heart on last summer’s cursed excursion became instead a parable for… something. Repairing an engine is merely logistics and expense; it takes about a month. Repairing a knee takes longer but costs less. Repairing a heart costs dearly, takes forever, and probably has very little to do with parables, engines, ligaments, Rabbits Jade, Bunnies Lola, or bouldering generally. 

But the body is where the heart resides, and I've set mine to task.
Nearly did it first session w/ Nat… first go of session four! Skin matters so very much. Thank you for holding me then and from afar, Nat.
Stuck the missing heel move first try, refreshed the other bits, then sat and delivered. 3 of 3. First ever trip-dub, as prophesied.

This climb is V11. I don’t know why I didn’t like starting with my right foot in the past. Seemed obvious this time. w/ Leo and Cisco spotting, shouting, and 'ken-domming' some strung-up ball and stickcup thingy
The utter delight of settling unfinished business.  I've probably tried this boulder over 200 times. Thank you, Zach, for supporting me through what hurt me on consecutive summers. Now you.
Thank you, Leona! It's kinda un-possible to number the difficulty of a flash; this boulder could be anything. Mostly, though, it is an arete climb. And a leg climb... as are all boulders.
Things are different now. I am 36, for one. feat. cake by Leona and fleur by Zach. Be full, my heart.
Super fun. After dropping the top of the Deputy three times in a row... Enter Bicep Tendonitis.
Came together really fast. Onsighting the four with no pads was a lil spooky. Really fun climb
Thanks and <3 to my Quebecoisquad for nudging me up the underwhelming, lesser line that lives in the shadow of Trickytoe, Sickytoe... trip dub #2 secured by headlamp!

Heel hook, hand up, hand up, hand down, hand up. Thanks to Beatrice for helping me process my compounding Deputy disappointment/ nauseating bicep tendonopathy with a tour of where fairies have been living. And thanks to Leona for being.
'This is not v10.' FOH...damn. Some v10s are v7, ever heard of it?!

Toast's favorite climbing area...yet.
This could be v11 or v10 or v9.
Met some really lovely people here this year. What a dream it'd be to live here.
Same as Defender of the Faith.

Sweet, sweet release of a sentence started in 2018. What a joy to feel undeniable progress. Thanks Coco & Phil for the hang, and  Hal for the verbal boost after I dropped the last hold like a wung-out chicken.

Laying pipe for greater things in 2026? Yes.
Securing the trip-dub, thereby making this last month the trip of trip trip-dub? Yes. Yes. I said Yes.

A more enjoyable climb than I ever suspected. Started with left hand pinching broken glass shards, right hand on sharp gravel sloper on the arete at eye-level. Hilariously sharp and constantly breaking, this climb is a case study in 'difficulty' being a slippery (& sharp) abstraction. Boy is this climb sharp. I broke the sit some more, adding sharpness and 'difficulty' and additional sharpness.
